  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">MA Horticulture Production and Marketing Capacity Building Project</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support the science and practice of food, feed, and fiber production (including forestry, wildlife, fisheries, aquaculture and floriculture) and its relationships to natural resources, processing, marketing, distribution, utilization (including nutrition), and trade.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This award strives to generate rapid, sustained, and broad-based economic growth. More specifically, this includes a Sector: Irrigated agriculture.Beneficiaries: 357 producers and 745 employees .Description: The project will improve access to inputs through revolving loan fund and strengthened access to bank loans to enable farmers to increase acreage and yields; establish solar-powered boreholes to increase cropping cycles and save on energy costs and provide a solar powered cold-room to store perishable produce and reduce post-harvest losses of fresh groundnuts and tomatoes. The assistance will improve the capacity of management to direct and control operations at MA through strengthening internal controls and establishing a business plan, policies and procedures, training in post-harvest handling and storage, enterprise planning, and corporate governance, agronomy and use of good agricultural systems and standards and financial literacy.. Sector: Irrigated agriculture Beneficiaries: 357 producers and 745 employees Description: The project will improve access to inputs through revolving loan fund and strengthened access to bank loans to enable farmers to increase acreage and yields; establish solar-powered boreholes to increase cropping cycles and save on energy costs and provide a solar powered cold-room to store perishable produce and reduce post-harvest losses of fresh groundnuts and tomatoes. The assistance will improve the capacity of management to direct and control operations at MA through strengthening internal controls and establishing a business plan, policies and procedures, training in post-harvest handling and storage, enterprise planning, and corporate governance, agronomy and use of good agricultural systems and standards and financial literacy..</narrative>
  </description>
